anguage|Japanese]], [[Okinawan language|Okinawan]], [[Ainu language|Ainu]]\n| [[Japan]]\n|-\n| '''[[Javanese alphabet|Javanese]]''' <br/> {{jav|\ua997\ua9ae}}\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0080000}}80<ref group=\"note\">Since around 1945 Javanese script has largely been supplanted by Latin script to write Javanese.</ref>\n| [[Javanese language|Javanese]]\n| Central [[Java]] (Indonesia), [[:Category:Javanese diaspora|Javanese diaspora]]\n|-\n| '''[[Hangul]]''' <br/> \ud55c\uae00 <br/> \uc870\uc120\uae00\n| [[Alphabet]], [[Featural alphabet|featural]]\n| {{hs|0078700}}78.7<ref group=\"note\">Excluding figures related to North Korea, which does not publish literacy rates.</ref>\n| [[Korean language|Korean]]\n| [[Korea]] ([[North Korea|North]] and [[South Korea|South]]), [[Jilin Province|Jilin Province (China)]]\n|-\n| '''[[Telugu script|Telugu]]''' <br/> \u0c24\u0c46\u0c32\u0c41\u0c17\u0c41\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0045000}}74<ref group=\"note\">Based on 61.11% literacy rate in Andhra Pradesh (according to government estimate) and 74 million [[Telugu language|Telugu speakers]].</ref>\n| [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Telangana]], [[Puducherry]] (India)\n|-\n| '''[[Tamil script|Tamil]]''' <br/> \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bcd\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0070000}}70<ref group=\"note\">Tamil Nadu has an estimated 80% literacy rate and about 72 million Tamil speakers.</ref><ref group=\"note\">Sri Lanka Tamil and Moor population that use Tamil script. 92% literacy</ref>\n| [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| [[Tamil Nadu]] (India), [[Puducherry]] (India), [[Sri Lanka]], [[Singapore]], [[Malaysia]], [[Mauritius]]\n|-\n| '''[[Gujarati script|Gujarati]]''' <br/> \u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac0\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0030000}}48<ref group=\"note\">Based on 60.38 million population and 79.31% literacy rate of [[Gujarat]]</ref>\n| [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]], [[Vasavi language|Vasavi]], [[Sanskrit]], [[Avestan]]\n| [[India]]<ref group=\"note\">An estimated 46 million Gujaratis live in India with 11 Gujarati-script newspapers in circulation.</ref>, [[Pakistan]]<ref group=\"note\">An estimated 1 million Gujaratis live in Pakistan with 2 Gujarati-script newspapers in circulation.</ref>\n|-\n| '''[[Kannada script|Kannada]]''' <br/> \u0c95\u0ca8\u0ccd\u0ca8\u0ca1\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0045000}}45<ref group=\"note\">Based on 46 million speakers of [[Kannada language]], [[Tulu language|Tulu]], [[Konkani]], [[Kodava language|Kodava]], [[Badaga language|Badaga]] in a state with a 75.6 literacy rate. url=http://updateox.com/india/26-populated-cities-karnataka-population-sex-ratio-literacy</ref>\n| [[Kannada language|Kannada]]\n| [[Karnataka]] (India)\n|-\n| '''[[Burmese script|Burmese]]''' <br/> \u1019\u103c\u1014\u103a\u1019\u102c\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0039000}}39<ref group=\"note\">Based on 42 million speakers of [[Burmese language|Burmese]] in a country ([[Myanmar]]) with a 92% [[Education in Burma|literacy rate]].</ref>\n| [[Burmese language|Burmese]]\n| [[Myanmar]]\n|-\n| '''[[Malayalam script|Malayalam]]''' <br/> \u0d2e\u0d32\u0d2f\u0d3e\u0d33\u0d02\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0052000}}38<ref group=\"note\">Spoken by 38 million people in the world.</ref>\n| [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]\n| [[Kerala]], [[Puducherry]] (India)\n|-\n| '''[[Thai script|Thai]]''' <br/> \u0e44\u0e17\u0e22\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0038000}}38<ref group=\"note\">Based on 40 million proficient speakers in a country with a 94% literacy rate.</ref>\n| [[Thai language|Thai]], [[Southern Thai language|Southern Thai]], [[Northern Khmer language|Northern Khmer]] and [[Lao language|Lao]] ([[Isan language|Isan]])\n| [[Thailand]]\n|-\n| '''[[Sundanese alphabet|Sundanese]]''' <br/> {{Sund|\u1b9e\u1ba5\u1b94\u1baa\u1b93}}\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0038000}}38\n| [[Sundanese language|Sundanese]]\n| [[Java]], Indonesia\n|-\n| '''[[Gurmukhi]]''' <br/> \u0a17\u0a41\u0a30\u0a2e\u0a41\u0a16\u0a40\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0100000}}22<ref group=\"note\">Based on 29 million Eastern Punjabi speakers and 75% literacy rate</ref>\n| [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n| [[Punjab]] (India)\n|-\n| '''[[Lao script|Lao]]''' <br/> \u0ea5\u0eb2\u0ea7\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0022000}}22<ref group=\"note\">Based on 30 million speakers of [[Lao language|Lao]] in a country with a 73% literacy.</ref>\n| [[Lao language|Lao]]\n| [[Laos]]\n|-\n| '''[[Oriya alphabet|Odia]]''' <br/> \u0b09\u0b24\u0b4d\u0b15\u0b33\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0021000}}21<ref group=\"note\">Based on 32 million speakers of [[Odia language|Odia]] in a country with a 65% literacy.</ref>\n| [[Odia language|Odia]]\n| [[Odisha]] (India)\n|-\n| '''[[Ge'ez script|Ge'ez]]''' <br/> \u130d\u12d5\u12dd\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0018000}}18<ref group=\"note\">Based on 30 million native speakers of Amharic and Tigrinya and a 60% literacy rate.</ref>\n| [[Amharic]], [[Tigrinya language|Tigrinya]]\n| [[Ethiopia]], [[Eritrea]]\n|-\n| '''[[Sinhala alphabet|Sinhala]]''' <br/> \u0dc3\u0dd2\u0d82\u0dc4\u0dbd\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0014400}}14.4<ref group=\"note\">Based on 15.6 million [[Sinhalese language|Sinhalese language speakers]] and a 92% [[Education in Sri Lanka|literacy rate]] in Sri Lanka.</ref>\n| [[Sinhala language|Sinhalese]]\n| [[Sri Lanka]]\n|-\n| '''[[Hebrew script|Hebrew]]''' <br/> \u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea\n| [[Abjad]]\n| {{hs|0014000}}14<ref group=\"note\">Hebrew has over 9 million speakers, including other Jewish languages and Jewish population outside Israel, where the Hebrew script is used by Jews for religious purposes worldwide.</ref>\n| [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] and other [[Jewish languages]]\n| [[Israel]]\n|-\n|'''[[Armenian script|Armenian]]''' <br/> \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0581\n| [[Alphabet]]\n| {{hs|0012000}}12\n| [[Armenian language|Armenian]]\n| [[Armenia]]\n|-\n| '''[[Khmer script|Khmer]]''' <br/> \u1781\u17d2\u1798\u17c2\u179a\n| [[Abugida]]\n| {{hs|0011400}}11.4<ref group=\"note\">Based on 15 million [[Khmer language|Khmer speakers]] with 73.6% [[Educa